{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17600959","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17600959"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T12:09:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T12:09:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15640"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15640","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15640"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.33,0.52,0.1,0,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8331"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71019"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8331","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8331"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15640"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56490"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7010"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20097"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20100"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71019","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/71019"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents with resistant hypertension and hypokalaemia. Investigations reveal elevated plasma aldosterone concentration and suppressed plasma renin activity, confirming primary aldosteronism.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely underlying cause of primary aldosteronism in this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Bilateral idiopathic hyperplasia","Aldosterone-producing adenoma","Familial hyperaldosteronism","Adrenal carcinoma","Unilateral adrenal hyperplasia"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBilateral idiopathic hyperplasia\u003C/strong\u003E is the most common cause of primary aldosteronism, accounting for approximately 60% of cases. The second most common cause is \u003Cstrong\u003Ealdosterone-producing adenoma\u003C/strong\u003E, accounting for about 30% of cases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other options are much less common:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFamilial hyperaldosteronism\u003C/strong\u003E accounts for less than 1% of cases\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdrenal carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E is an extremely rare cause of primary aldosteronism\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUnilateral adrenal hyperplasia\u003C/strong\u003E is also a rare cause\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGiven the presentation with resistant hypertension and hypokalaemia, and the fact that bilateral idiopathic hyperplasia is the most common cause, this is the most likely diagnosis in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Bilateral idiopathic hyperplasia accounts for approximately 60% of primary aldosteronism cases","Aldosterone-producing adenoma accounts for approximately 30% of primary aldosteronism cases","Other causes of primary aldosteronism including familial forms and carcinoma are rare"],"references":["Scott JH, Menouar MA, Dunn RJ. Physiology, Aldosterone. [Updated 2023 May 1]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK470339/","Melmed, S., Polonsky, K. S., Larsen, P. R., \u0026 Kronenberg, H. M. (2015). Williams textbook of endocrinology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Clark, O. H., Duh, Q. Y., Kebebew, E., Gosnell, J. E., \u0026 Shen, W. T. (Eds.). (2016). Textb